I built my very first speaker when I was nine. You can use it as a mid bass woofer. It even looks like something you could buy because it has a metal frame just like on retail speakers. It has a spider, tinsel leads, a dust cap, nylon surround, terminals and a ceramic magnet ring with a metal pillar. It moves freely without scratching and has a lot of bass. It’s a five inch speaker. The coil has a proper former and the wire is coiled up twice precisely and glued onto the former all the way through so it’s attached firmly onto the former. The frame has four screw holes and the woofer replaced a broken Logitech subwoofer. The build was a massive success and the system sounds nice. But it’s not very powerful because of the lack of cooling and excursion.

Decibel-meter apps aren't worth anything because they're not calibrated and therefore the reading is meaningless.
You don't measure the power of a speaker like that at all. Since decibels are heavily affected by distance, the correct standard way is measuring with 1W power, 1 meter away.

So no, it's not averaging 70 dB, that would be uncomfortably loud.
